'''Dennis A. Tirpak''' is an expert on [[Climate Change]]. He is a Senior Fellow at the [[World Resources Institute]].

Tirpak was the director of the Global Climate Change Policy Division at the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency]] in 1984-1992. He was the Coordinator of Science and Technology at the [[United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change]] for nine years. He was the head of the climate change unit at the [[Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development]] (OECD) for three years. He has also worked on the [[Montreal Protocol]], and held positions in industry with [[Texaco]], [[Alcoa]], and [[Braddock Dunn & McDonald]].  His awards include an EPA Gold Medal, a U.S. Government Senior Executive Service Award, and a President’s Commission on Personnel Interchange Award.<ref>[https://www.acs.org/content/acs/en/policy/acsonthehill/briefings/greenhousegas/bio-tirpak.html https://www.acs.org/content/acs/en/policy/acsonthehill/briefings/greenhousegas/bio-tirpak.html]</ref>

Tirpak is one of the coordinating lead authors of the [[Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change]], which shared the [[2007 Nobel Peace Prize]] with former US Vice President [[Al Gore]]. He advises national governments and industry as an associate of the [[International Institute for Sustainable Development]] in Canada, and a senior fellow at the [[World Resources Institute]] in Washington, D.C.

Tirpak was the Chairman of the International Scientific Steering Committee for [[Avoiding dangerous climate change#A 2005 scientific symposium on avoiding dangerous climate change|Avoiding Dangerous Climate Change Symposium on Stabilisation of Greenhouse Gas Concentrations]], which took place at the invitation of the British Prime Minister [[Tony Blair]] in February 2005.

In 1989 he and Joel B. Smith <ref>[https://www.abtassociates.com/who-we-are/our-people/experts/joel-b-smith https://www.abtassociates.com/who-we-are/our-people/experts/joel-b-smit ]</ref> co-authored the first report on global warming to Congress, ''The Potential Effects Of Global Climate Change on the United States''<ref>[http://www.ciesin.org/docs/001-328/001-328.html http://www.ciesin.org/docs/001-328/001-328.html]</ref>.

Tirpak has written a scientific and policy history on climate change and contributed to many publications including ''[[The New York Times]]'' in an op-ed titled "How Green is My Taxi" (April 22, 2007)<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2007/04/22/opinion/nyregionopinions/22CItirpak.html https://www.nytimes.com/2007/04/22/opinion/nyregionopinions/22CItirpak.html]</ref>

