{{update|date=September 2014}} {{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}} {{Use British English|date=September 2013}} {{Infobox UK legislation |short_title = Energy Act 2013 |parliament = Parliament of the United Kingdom |long_title = An Act to make provision for the setting of a decarbonisation target range and duties in relation to it; for or in connection with reforming the electricity market for purposes of encouraging low carbon electricity generation or ensuring security of supply; for the establishment and functions of the Office for Nuclear Regulation; about the government pipe-line and storage system and rights exercisable in relation to it; about the designation of a strategy and policy statement; about domestic supplies of gas and electricity; for extending categories of activities for which energy licences are required; for the making of orders requiring regulated persons to provide redress to consumers of gas or electricity; about offshore transmission of electricity during a commissioning period; for imposing fees in connection with certain costs incurred by the Secretary of State; and for connected purposes. |statute_book_chapter = |introduced_by = [[Ed Davey]] |territorial_extent = England, Wales, Scotland |royal_assent = 18 December 2013 |commencement = |repeal_date = |amendments = |related_legislation = [[Energy Act 2010]] |repealing_legislation= |status = Not_fully_in_force |original_text = https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/bills/cbill/2012-2013/0135/2013135.pdf |use_new_UK-LEG = no |legislation_history = http://services.parliament.uk/bills/2012-13/energy.html }}
The '''Energy Act 2013''' is an [[Act of Parliament|Act]] of the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]], relating to the energy sector. It succeeded the [[Energy Act 2010]]. The Act focuses on setting [[decarbonisation]] targets for the UK, and reforming the electricity market. The Act was intended by [[Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change]] [[Ed Davey]] to "attract investment to bring about a once-in-a-generation transformation of our electricity market".<ref name=nuclear>{{cite web|last=Bakewell|first=Sally|title=U.K. Nuclear Push Gains With Bill to Revamp Power Market|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-11-29/u-k-nuclear-push-advances-with-bill-to-revamp-power-market.html|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=26 February 2013}}</ref>
==History== The Energy Bill was introduced by the government in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] for [[first reading]] on 29 November 2012,<ref>{{cite web|title=Bill Documents|url=http://services.parliament.uk/bills/2012-13/energy/documents.html|publisher=UK Parliament|accessdate=26 February 2013}}</ref> and passed a vote at third reading with cross-party support on 4 June 2013. The Bill received Royal Assent on 18 December 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Energy Act 2013|url=http://services.parliament.uk/bills/2012-13/energy.html|publisher=UK Parliament|accessdate=19 June 2015}}</ref>
==Aims== The Act aims to maintain a stable electricity supply as [[coal-fired power station]]s are retired.<ref name=nuclear/> This includes facilitating the building of a new set of [[nuclear power station]]s and the establishment of a new [[regulatory agency|regulator]], the [[Office for Nuclear Regulation]].
The Act proposes a delay in setting decarbonisation targets under the [[Climate Change Act 2008]], until 2016. Businesses and analysts have criticised the uncertainty this causes for investors, notably [[Balfour Beatty]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Energy Bill amendment could boost green construction|url=http://www.building.co.uk/sustainability/sustainability-news/energy-bill-amendment-could-boost-green-construction/5050066.article|publisher=Building.co.uk|accessdate=26 February 2013}}</ref> and [[Ernst & Young]].<ref>{{cite web|title="Once in a generation" UK Energy Bill falls short of expectations |url=http://www.commodities-now.com/reports/power-and-energy/13955-once-in-a-generation-uk-energy-bill-falls-short-of-expectations.html |publisher=Commodities Now |accessdate=26 February 2013 }}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Conservative MP [[Tim Yeo]] and Labour MP [[Barry Gardiner]] tabled amendments to the Bill to reinsert a 2030 decarbonisation target for the power sector by 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sticking point? -- The 2030 decarbonisation target debate|url=http://www.cornwallenergy.com/Opinion/Sticking-point-The-2030-decarbonisation-target-debate|website=Cornwall Energy|accessdate=23 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Hopes for green investment boost from Energy Bill amendment|url=http://www.bdonline.co.uk/sustainability/hopes-for-green-investment-boost-from-energy-bill-amendment/5050434.article|accessdate=26 February 2013}}</ref>
The Act also enables the government to privatise the [[Government Pipelines and Storage System]].
