{{BLP sources|date=May 2010}} '''Lisa Lyttelton, Dowager Viscountess Cobham''' (born about 1958 as '''Lisa Clayton''') is the first [[United Kingdom|British]] woman to [[sailing|sail]] [[single-handed sailing|single-handed]] and non-stop around the world.<ref>{{cite news|title=British sailor Lisa Clayton|work=Star-News|date=1995-06-30|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=5q4sAAAAIBAJ&sjid=FBUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4204,5559161|accessdate=2010-05-17}}</ref> She was educated in [[Birmingham]] at the [[St George's School, Birmingham|Church of England School for Girls, Edgbaston]], and the [[University of Birmingham]].<ref>{{cite web|title=His Lordship ties the knot with lady skipper|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/his-lordship-ties-the-knot-with-lady-skipper-1243968.html|website=The Independent|accessdate=17 January 2015}}</ref>
On 17 September 1994 Clayton set out to attempt two [[world record]]s, namely "Fastest Sail Around the World by a Woman, Single-Handed Without Assistance" and "First British Woman to Sail Single-Handed and Non-Stop Around the World." She returned on 29 June 1995, after 285 days at sea.
On her thirty-eight foot [[yacht]], called ''Spirit of Birmingham'', Clayton survived the {{convert|31000|mi|km|sing=on}} journey despite capsizing seven times. Her vessel was named after her home city and the [[university]] which contributed over £40,000 and expertise to make it possible for Clayton to realise her dream. On 1 October 1996, Clayton was recognised as an Honorary Freeman of the City of Birmingham.<ref>{{cite web|title=Freedom Parades and Freedom of the City|url=http://birmingham.gov.uk/cs/Satellite?c=Page&childpagename=Lord-Mayor%2FPageLayout&cid=1223244011251&pagename=BCC%2FCommon%2FWrapper%2FWrapper&rendermode=live|website=Birmingham City Council|accessdate=17 January 2015}}</ref>
On 1 August 1997 she married the [[John Lyttelton, 11th Viscount Cobham|11th Viscount Cobham]], owner of [[Hagley Hall]] in [[Worcestershire]]. He died in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|title=Obituary: Viscount Cobham|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2006/jul/22/guardianobituaries.mainsection1|website=The Guardian|accessdate=17 January 2015}}</ref>
