{{Unreferenced stub|auto=yes|date=December 2009}}
An '''octatomic element''' is a [[chemical element]] that, when [[standard conditions for temperature and pressure]] is stable, is in a configuration of eight atoms grouped together. The canonical example is [[sulphur]], S<sub>8</sub>, but red [[selenium]] is also an octatomic element stable at room temperature. [[Octaoxygen]] is also known, but it is extremely unstable.

==See also==
