{{thermodynamics|cTopic=Processes and Cycles}}
A '''transcritical cycle''' is a [[thermodynamic cycle]] where the working fluid goes through both [[Superheated_water|Subcritical]] and [[Supercritical fluid|supercritical]] states. This is often the case when [[carbon dioxide]], CO<sub>2</sub>, is the [[refrigerant]].

The modern transcritical cycle was developed in 1988–1991 by the Norwegian professor [[Gustav Lorentzen (scientist)|Gustav Lorentzen]] (1915–1995) and his team.<ref>Shecco Synergies, Hydro, Oslo 2003. www.shecco.com</ref>



